🔧 How to actually use mosaics in Pantheon

1. Mosaic = your universal data structure

Instead of thinking:
	•	list of features
	•	flat embeddings

Think:

everything is a tile in a mosaic field

Each tile has:

position: (x, y, z)
value: signal / meaning
confidence: 0–1
type: object / relation / anomaly / symbol
time: timestamp

Now:
	•	RTFIE outputs mosaics
	•	agents operate on mosaics
	•	memory stores mosaics

⸻

2. Mosaic layers (critical)

Layer 1 — Signal Tiles
	•	raw detections
	•	colors, objects, edges, wear

Layer 2 — Pattern Tiles
	•	relationships
	•	clusters
	•	inferred structures

Layer 3 — Constraint Tiles
	•	pressures
	•	limitations
	•	causal forces

Layer 4 — Narrative Tiles
	•	meaning
	•	interpretation
	•	story fragments

Each layer overlays the same space.

⸻

3. Mosaic operations (this is where it gets powerful)

A. Zoom (scale transform)
	•	zoom in → debug details
	•	zoom out → see system behavior

⸻

B. Tile weighting
	•	some tiles matter more
	•	attention engine (Badger) controls this

⸻

C. Tile replacement
	•	update one tile without breaking the whole

This gives you:

reversibility at the micro level

⸻

D. Tile clustering
	•	form patterns from local groups

That’s your inference layer.

⸻

E. Gap detection
	•	missing tiles = missing information

That’s your Hound reflex:

“what should be here but isn’t?”

⸻

4. Agents as mosaic operators

This is clean:

Agent	Mosaic Role
Hound	detects broken / anomalous tiles
Mirror	checks tile consistency
Dragonfly	rearranges tile perspectives
Spider	assembles final mosaic output
Raven	compresses mosaic into minimal form
Badger	controls which tiles are visible
Hypatia	ensures structural validity of tile relations

Now everything speaks the same language.

⸻

5. Mosaic memory (this is big)

Instead of storing:
	•	text
	•	logs
	•	random embeddings

Store:

time-indexed mosaics

Then you can:
	•	compare mosaics over time
	•	detect drift
	•	see evolution of structure

This becomes:

archaeology + forecasting in one

⸻

6. Mosaic + RTFIE = 🔥

RTFIE currently:
	•	extracts signals
	•	builds hypotheses

Upgrade it to:

construct a live mosaic of the scene

Then:
	•	hypotheses operate on tile clusters
	•	uncertainty = tile confidence
	•	contradictions = conflicting tiles

⸻

7. Mosaic as interface

Instead of just text output, you could think:
	•	summary = macro mosaic view
	•	detail = zoomed tiles
	•	uncertainty = fuzzy edges
	•	conflict = overlapping tiles

Even if you never visualize it, thinking this way keeps structure clean.

